Hi all, 
I just wanted to clarify a bit the behavior I am seeing in my case with this. 

It never looks like the code enters the session_ended function. You can allow the reprompt timer to expire, but you can also say "exit" to the skill and force a "user initiated" close. In my case I saw the same behavior when allowing the timer to expire, and when trying to manually exit the skill. 

I know this because I inserted a log into the session_ended function and it is never printed to screen.  

@ask.session_ended
def session_ended():
    log.debug("\n\nHit closing event handler\n\n")
    return statement("")


So what I tried to do then was kind of over ride the Exit keyword with my own exit function. I then setup an utterance to call this new ExitIntent when I say the word 'cancel'.

 @ask.intent("ExitIntent")
 def exit_code():
     log.debug("\n\nHit Exit Intent!!!!\n\n")
     session_ended()


This way I could see how it behaves. And that had a similar effect. The strange part was when calling the session_ended function through my own exit intent function, I actually saw both debug statements print (the one in my exitintent, and the one in the sessionended intent) but I received the same NoneType object is not iterable message. 

