Concerning metadata. I think that for now you can combine the metadata into a dictionary by `run_id` and/or `run_name` within a dedicated field, smth like:
```
{
    merged_runs: {
        25: {'snapshot': {...}},
        37: {'snapshot': {...}},
    },
    < other meta data of THIS dataset >
}
```
I think the metadata is going to be a "place for dumping stuff" anyway, hence it is just not easy to say how to perform "operations" on it. So, a simple solution like this is probably fine as long as minimal "separation"/"organization" measures are taken.

In my case I need the server-side flow (in order to use the social-auth pipelines.)

Here's my version, using the Google ```tokeninfo``` endpoint.
Now i'm getting the email address (enough for me at this moment)

```py
class CustomGooglePlusAuth(GooglePlusAuth):
    def user_data(self, access_token, *args, **kwargs):
      params = dict(id_token=access_token)
      resp = requests.get(url='https://www.googleapis.com/oauth2/v3/tokeninfo', params=params)
      return json.loads(resp.text)
```

@eric-jj , @guoyuhong , @pcmoritz , @robertnishihara here is a draft of the product requirements document for jobs: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1XarOe4QKKcFbHRzy-OH5gGQz25dNBl3tCWDK-9oOyEY/edit#

We should make sure that the design of the "garbage collection" is consistent with jobs. They clearly have overlapping requirements, and don't want to have multiple APIs or implementations.

Regarding the `with` API we need to make sure that it provides the developer with the ability to (1) get an unique ID of the job's execution, (2) specify whether to perform garbage collection, or not, on job's completion, and (3) get status of the job's execution (while this is not a part of the "must" requirements for now, the question is not whether to do it but when).

